        <p><strong>Important pricing note:</strong> Buildxact pricing varies by region (US vs. Australia/NZ) and is updated periodically. Verify current US pricing at Buildxact's website. A 14-day free trial is available without a credit card.</p>

        <h2>Core features</h2>

        <h3>Digital takeoff</h3>
        <p>Buildxact's digital takeoff lets you upload PDF plans and measure quantities directly from the drawings. Linear measurements, area calculations, and count tools cover the primary residential takeoff needs. The takeoff connects directly to your estimate — measured quantities auto-populate the corresponding estimate line items, reducing the manual transfer step that introduces errors in separate takeoff tools.</p>

        <p>The takeoff is competent for residential work. It's not as fast or as feature-rich as dedicated tools like Stack or PlanSwift, but for builders who don't do dozens of estimates per month, it's sufficient.</p>

        <h3>Estimating</h3>
        <p>Buildxact's estimating system uses a recipe/assembly approach — you create assemblies (e.g., "100mm concrete slab" = concrete + formwork + reinforcing at specific rates per square meter or foot) that auto-calculate material and labor costs when quantities are entered. Your cost libraries build up over time as you use the system, and historical job costs can be reviewed to refine future estimates.</p>

        <p>The supplier pricing integration (available in Australia/NZ primarily, limited in US) lets you pull live material prices from participating suppliers into your estimates. This is a significant time-saver when current material costs are volatile.</p>

        <h3>Proposals and quotes</h3>
        <p>From your estimate, Buildxact generates client-facing quotes and proposals. The output is professional — itemized or summary format, with your company logo and contact information. Clients can review and sign off digitally. For residential builders who currently email PDF quotes built in Word, this is a meaningful upgrade.</p>

        <h3>Job management</h3>
        <p>Once a quote is accepted, Buildxact converts it to an active job. The job management features include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Basic Gantt scheduling with task dependencies</li>
          <li>Purchase order creation from estimate line items</li>
          <li>Bill entry and budget vs. actual tracking</li>
          <li>Progress invoicing to clients</li>
          <li>Basic subcontractor management</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Client communication</h3>
        <p>A basic client portal lets homeowners track project progress, view the schedule, and access shared documents. It's less sophisticated than Buildertrend's client portal (no homeowner selections management, for example), but covers the essential "keep the client informed" use case.</p>

        <h3>QuickBooks integration</h3>
        <p>Buildxact integrates with QuickBooks Online for US users, syncing invoices and purchase orders. The integration covers the basics but isn't as deep as Buildertrend's two-way sync. Expect some manual reconciliation.</p>

        <h2>What Buildxact does well</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Integrated takeoff-to-estimate workflow — no separate tools needed for basic residential estimating</li>
          <li>Affordable entry price for builders who can't justify Buildertrend's cost</li>
          <li>14-day free trial with no credit card required</li>
          <li>Assembly-based estimating builds efficiency over time</li>
          <li>Solid proposal output for client-facing quotes</li>
          <li>Good for builders doing 1–15 projects simultaneously</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Where Buildxact falls short</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>US market maturity</strong> — Buildxact is more established in Australia/NZ. Some features (supplier pricing integration) are limited in the US</li>
          <li><strong>Client portal depth</strong> — No selections management, no change order approval workflow as polished as Buildertrend</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile app</strong> — Field-facing mobile experience is basic compared to Buildertrend or Fieldwire</li>
          <li><strong>Scheduling depth</strong> — Gantt scheduling exists but isn't as powerful as dedicated scheduling tools</li>
          <li><strong>Support</strong> — Based in Australia; US-timezone support response times can be slower</li>
          <li><strong>Integrations</strong> — Fewer third-party integrations than Buildertrend or Procore</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Buildxact vs. Buildertrend</h2>
        <p>The most common comparison for this audience:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Price:</strong> Buildxact ($149–$499/mo) vs. Buildertrend ($499–$1,099/mo) — Buildxact is significantly cheaper</li>
          <li><strong>Takeoff:</strong> Both include digital takeoff; similar depth for residential use</li>
          <li><strong>Client portal:</strong> Buildertrend is meaningfully better — richer selections management, better change order workflows</li>
          <li><strong>US market support:</strong> Buildertrend has larger US team and support resources</li>
          <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Buildxact works for builders under $2M/year; Buildertrend is stronger for $2M+ operations</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Who Buildxact is for</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Small residential builders and remodelers (under $2M annual revenue)</li>
          <li>Custom homebuilders doing 1–8 homes per year</li>
          <li>Builders currently estimating in Excel who want an integrated system</li>
          <li>Contractors who want takeoff + estimating + basic PM in one affordable tool</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

        <h3>Is Buildxact available in the US?</h3>
        <p>Yes — Buildxact has been actively expanding in the US market. Pricing, supplier integrations, and some features are more developed in the Australian/NZ market where Buildxact originated, but the core platform is fully functional for US builders.</p>

        <h3>Does Buildxact have a free trial?</h3>
        <p>Yes — Buildxact offers a 14-day free trial without requiring a credit card. This is enough time to run through a realistic estimate and evaluate whether the workflow fits your business.</p>

        <h3>What accounting software does Buildxact integrate with?</h3>
        <p>QuickBooks Online and MYOB (Australia/NZ). Xero integration is available in some markets. For US contractors, QuickBooks Online is the primary accounting integration.</p>

